\"background-color:#00CC99\" | #5 Texas <br> 105\u201354\n|style=\"background-color:#00CC99\" | #7 Dayton <br> 91\u201370\n|style=\"background-color:#00CC99\" | #1 Maryland <br> 81\u201358\n|style=\"background-color:#00CC99\" | #1 Notre Dame <br> 63\u201353\n|- \n|[[2016 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|2016]] \n|#1\n|style=\"background-color:#00CC99\" | #16 Robert Morris <br> 101\u201349\n|style=\"background-color:#00CC99\" | #9 Duquesne <br> 91\u201357\n|style=\"background-color:#00CC99\" | #5 Mississippi State <br> 98\u201338\n|style=\"background-color:#00CC99\" | #2 Texas <br> 86\u201365\n|style=\"background-color:#00CC99\" | #2 Oregon State <br> 80\u201351\n|style=\"background-color:#00CC99\" | #4 Syracuse <br> 82\u201351\n|- \n|[[2017 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|2017]] \n|#1\n|style=\"background-color:#00CC99\" | #16 Albany <br> 116\u201355\n|style=\"background-color:#00CC99\" | #8 Syracuse <br> 94\u201364\n|style=\"background-color:#00CC99\" | #4 UCLA <br> 86\u201371\n|style=\"background-color:#00CC99\" | #10 Oregon <br> 90-52\n|style=\"background-color:#FF0000\" | #2 Mississippi State <br> 64-66 <small>(OT)</small>\n|\n|- \n|[[2018 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|2018]] \n|#1\n|style=\"background-color:#00CC99\" | #16 St. Francis <br> 140\u201352\n|style=\"background-color:#00CC99\" | #9 Quinnipiac <br> 71-46\n|style=\"background-color:#00CC99\" | #5 Duke <br> 72-59\n|style=\"background-color:#00CC99\" | #2 South Carolina <br> 94-65\n|style=\"background-color:#FF0000\" | #1 Notre Dame <br> 89-91 <small>(OT)</small>\n|\n|- \n|[[2019 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|2019]] \n|#2\n|style=\"background-color:#00CC99\" | #15 Towson <br> 110\u201361\n|style=\"background-color:#00CC99\" | #10 Buffalo <br> 84-72\n|style=\"background-color:#00CC99\" | #6 UCLA <br> 69-61\n|style=\"background-color:#00CC99\" | #1 Louisville <br> 80-73\n|style=\"background-color:#FF0000\" | #1 Notre Dame <br> 76-81\n|\n|}\n\n==Head coaches==\n===Sandra Hamm (1974\u20131975)===\nSandra Hamm, a Terryville native, was employed part-time as the interim women's coach in the 1974-1975 season, when the team was 2-8. When she wasn't coaching, she taught physical education at a junior high school in Manchester.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Salzman|first1=Avi|title=UConn Basketball, Then and Now|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/04/18/nyregion/uconn-basketball-then-and-now.html?_r=0|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Wanda Flora (1975\u20131980)===\nAfter graduating from college in California, Wanda Flora went to graduate school at Indiana University, where she was an assistant coach for the women's basketball team and coached the junior varsity team. After a brief stint at a small college in Pennsylvania, she applied for the job at UConn, starting in 1975 and leading the team to a 38\u201366 record in five seasons. During her tenure, shooting guard Karen Mullins was the first UConn woman to receive a basketball scholarship; that number had increased to 12 by 1980.\n\n===Jean Balthaser (1980\u20131985)===\nIn 1980 the university hired Jean Balthaser, who had coached at the University of Pittsburgh. Ms. Balthaser continued to expand the program, leading UConn to its first winning season in her first year as coach, and finishing with a 52-88 record over five seasons.\n\n===Geno Auriemma (1985\u2013present)===\nIn his 34 years as head coach of the University of Connecticut women\u2019s basketball team, the Italian-born [[Geno Auriemma|Luigi \"Geno\" Auriemma]] has inextricably linked his name with that of the team. Inheriting a program that had only had one winning season in its entire history, Auriemma has overseen one of the most successful rebuilding projects in college sports history. Under his watch, UConn has become the winningest team in women's college basketball, and he has made a strong case as one of the best coaches ever.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Baxter|first1=Kevin|title=Connecticut's Geno Auriemma keeps making a case to be considered the greatest basketball coach|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-uconn-auriemma-20160403-story.html|publisher=LA Times|accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Who's the best coach ever? Connecticut's Auriemma, that's who|url=http://www.daily-journal.com/opinion/editorials/who-s-the-best-coach-ever-connecticut-s-auriemma-that/article_a7e337c8-c055-59f2-9304-50da5a26b1d1.html|publisher=Daily Journal|accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Megdal|first1=Howard|title=Case for UConn's Geno Auriemma being best coach ever goes beyond basketball|url=http://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/case-for-uconns-geno-auriemma-being-best-coach-ever-goes-beyond-basketball/|publisher=cbssports.com|accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref> In his astonishing career Auriemma has won more than 25 different national Coach of the Year awards and was inducted into both the [[List of coaches in the Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame|Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame]] and the [[Women's Basketball Hall of Fame]]. He was head coach of the [[United States women's national basketball team]] from 2009 until stepping down from that role after the [[2016 Summer Olympics]]. During his tenure with Team USA, they won the [[2010 FIBA World Championship for Women|2010]] and [[2014 FIBA World Championship for Women|2014]] [[FIBA Women's Basketball World Cup|World Cups]],<!--While the tournaments were known as \"World Championships\" before the 2018 edition, FIBA considers all winners of its top women's championship to be 'World Cup\" winners.--> plus Olympic gold medals in [[Basketball at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2012]] and [[Basketball at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2016]].\n\n==Notable players==\n\n===Individual achievements===\nUConn has featured a great number of star players, All-Americans, Hall of Famers and recipients of individual trophies. The following table shows the UConn players recipients of the major individual awards in women's college basketball.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 16%;\" | Player \n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 14%;\" | [[Honda Sports Award (basketball)|Honda Sports Award]] <br /> (since 1977)\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 14%;\" | [[Wade Trophy]] <br /> (since 1978)\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 14%;\" | [[Naismith College Player of the Year]] <br /> (since 1983)\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 14%;\" | [[USBWA Women's National Player of the Year]] <br /> (since 1988)\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 14%;\" | [[Associated Press Women's College Basketball Player of the Year|AP College Player of the Year]] <br /> (since 1995)\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 14%;\" | [[John R. Wooden Award]] <br /> (since 2004)\n|-\n| [[Rebecca Lobo]] || 1995 || 1995 || 1995 || 1995 || 1995 || \n|-\n| [[Jennifer Rizzotti]] || 1996 || 1996 ||  ||  || 1996 || \n|-\n| [[Kara Wolters]] || ||  ||  ||  || 1997 || \n|-\n| [[Shea Ralph]] || 2000 ||  ||  ||  ||  || \n|-\n| [[Sue Bird]] || 2002 || 2002 || 2002 || 2002 || 2002 ||\n|-\n| [[Diana Taurasi]] || 2003 <br /> 2004 || 2003 || 2003 <br /> 2004  || 2003 || 2003 ||\n|-\n| [[Renee Montgomery]] || 2009 ||  ||  ||  ||  ||\n|-\n| [[Tina Charles (basketball)|Tina Charles]] || ||  || 2010 || 2010 || 2010 || 2010\n|-\n| [[Maya Moore]] || 2010 <br /> 2011 || 2009 <br /> 2010 <br /> 2011 || 2009 <br /> 2011 || 2009 <br /> 2011 || 2009 <br /> 2011 || 2009 <br /> 2011\n|-\n| [[Breanna Stewart]] || 2014 <br /> 2015 <br /> 2016 || 2015 <br /> 2016 || 2014 <br /> 2015 <br /> 2016 || 2014 <br /> 2015 <br /> 2016 || 2014 <br /> 2015 <br /> 2016 || 2015 <br /> 2016\n|}\n\nAfter the end of the NCAA tournament, the Associated Press selects a [[NCAA Basketball Tournament Most Outstanding Player|Most Outstanding Player]].\nSeven UConn players received this award since its induction in 1982: [[Rebecca Lobo]] (1995), [[Shea Ralph]] (2000), [[Swin Cash]] (2002), [[Diana Taurasi]] (2003 and 2004), [[Tina Charles (basketball)|Tina Charles]] (2009), [[Maya Moore]] (2010) and [[Breanna Stewart]] for a record 4 times (2013, 2014, 2015, 2016).\n\n=== School records ===\nStatistics correct through March 9, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|title=UConn Women's Basketball 2015-2016 Media Guide|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/conn/sports/w-baskbl/auto_pdf/2015-16/misc_non_event/w-baskbl-media-guide-16.pdf|accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nActive players in '''bold'''.\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n'''Most points (1000-point club)'''\n# [[Maya Moore]] (3,036)\n# [[Breanna Stewart]] (2,676)\n# [[Napheesa Collier]] (2,401)\n# [[Tina Charles (basketball)|Tina Charles]] (2,346)\n# [[Katie Lou Samuelson]]  (2,342)\n# [[Kaleena Mosqueda-Lewis]] (2,178)\n# [[Nykesha Sales]] (2,178)\n# [[Kerry Bascom]] (2,177)\n# [[Diana Taurasi]] (2,156)\n# [[Kara Wolters]] (2,141)\n# [[Rebecca Lobo]] (2,133)\n# [[Bria Hartley]] (1,994)\n# [[Renee Montgomery]] (1,990)\n# [[Svetlana Abrosimova]] (1,865)\n# [[Tiffany Hayes]] (1,801)\n# [[Stefanie Dolson]] (1,709)\n# [[Ann Strother]] (1,699)\n# [[Shea Ralph]] (1,678)\n# [[Kia Nurse]] (1,674)\n# [[Barbara Turner (basketball)|Barbara Turner]] (1,629)\n# [[Swin Cash]] (1,583)\n# [[Gabby Williams]] (1,582)\n# Wendy Davis (1,552)\n# [[Jennifer Rizzotti]] (1,540)\n# Cathy Bochain (1,534)\n# [[Moriah Jefferson]] (1,532)\n# [[Asjha Jones]] (1,502)\n# [[Crystal Dangerfield]] (1,480)\n# [[Kalana Greene]] (1,444)\n# Peggy Walsh (1,413)\n# Chris Gedney (1,409)\n# [[Tamika Williams]] (1,402)\n# Leigh Curl (1,388)\n# [[Jamelle Elliott]] (1,387)\n# Carla Berube (1,381)\n# [[Sue Bird]] (1,378)\n# [[Charde Houston]] (1,365)\n# Laura Lishness (1,303)\n# [[Morgan Tuck]] (1,298)\n# Megan Walker (1,251)\n# Kris Lamb (1,244)\n# [[Jessica Moore (basketball)|Jessica Moore]] (1,223)\n# [[Kelly Faris]] (1,109)\n# Megan Pattyson (1,106)\n# [[Mel Thomas]] (1,098)\n# [[Ashley Battle]] (1,054)\n# Amy Duran (1,000)\n\n\n{{col-